{{Infobox Artwork | image_file = Andrew Wyeth Public Sale.jpg | title = Public Sale | artist = [[Andrew Wyeth]] | year = 1943 | medium = [[Tempera]] on panel | height_metric = 56 | width_metric = 122 | height_imperial = 22 | width_imperial = 48 | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = [[Philadelphia]] | museum = [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] }} '''''Public Sale''''' is a 1943 painting by the American artist [[Andrew Wyeth]]. It shows two men by a car and in the distance a crowd of people outside a farm building. The event depicted is the forced auction of a farm after the farmer's wife had died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philamuseum.org/exhibitions/2006/93.html?page=2|title=Andrew Wyeth: Memory and Magic|publisher=[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]]|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref>
The painting belongs to the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] since 2000. As of 2016, it is currently not on view.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/93576.html|title=Public Sale|publisher=[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]]|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref>
==Reception== [[Ken Johnson (art critic)|Ken Johnson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' singled the painting out as unusual in Wyeth's oeuvre because it "evinces social consciousness", something that otherwise is absent from the artist's works and makes him different from his contemporary [[Norman Rockwell]]. Johnson, reviewing a Wyeth exhibition in 2006, likened ''Public Sale'' to "an understated [[Thomas Hart Benton (painter)|Thomas Hart Benton]] painting".<ref>{{Cite web|last=Johnson|first=Ken|date=April 18, 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/18/arts/design/18wyet.html|title='Andrew Wyeth: Memory and Magic' at the Philadelphia Museum of Art|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref>
